13 SUMMARY
1144 This amendment, which is the minority report of the committee, replaces the bill and
1155 changes the title.
16 The amendment enacts the Maine Consumer Data Privacy Act, which takes effect July
17 1, 2026. The Act regulates the collection, use, processing, disclosure, sale and deletion of
18 nonpublicly available personal data that is linked or reasonably linkable to an individual
19 who is a resident of the State, referred to in the Act as a "consumer," or that is linked or
20 reasonably linkable to an identifiable consumer's device, by a person that conducts business
21 in this State or that produces products or services targeted to residents of this State, referred
22 to in the Act as a "controller." Under the Act, a controller must limit the collection of
23 personal data to what is adequate, relevant and reasonably necessary in relation to the
24 purposes for which the controller processes that data, as disclosed in a privacy notice
25 specifying the categories of personal data processed by the controller, the purposes for
26 processing the personal data, the categories of personal data transferred to 3rd parties and
27 the categories of 3rd parties to whom personal data is shared. The controller must also
28 process the minimum amount of personal data reasonably necessary, adequate or relevant
29 for each disclosed processing purpose.
30 A consumer has the right, under the Act, to confirm whether a controller is processing
31 the consumer's personal data; to require the controller to correct inaccuracies in or delete
32 the consumer's personal data; to obtain a copy of the consumer's personal data; and to opt
33 out of the processing of the consumer's personal data for purposes of targeted advertising,
34 sale or profiling in furtherance of decisions about the consumer's access to financial or
35 lending services, housing, insurance, education, criminal justice, employment
36 opportunities, health care services and essential goods and services. The privacy notice
37 must describe how a consumer may exercise these rights. The controller must obtain the
38 affirmative, informed consent of a consumer before processing the consumer's sensitive
39 data, including data revealing the consumer's race or ethnic origins, religious beliefs,
40 medical history or mental or physical health conditions or diagnoses, sexual orientation or
41 citizenship or immigration status; genetic or biometric data; precise geolocation data; data
42 of a known child who has not attained 13 years of age; social security, driver's license or
43 nondriver identification card number; information that permits access to a consumer's
44 financial account; or data concerning the consumer's status as the victim of a crime. If the
Page 20 - 132LR0014(03)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 1220, L.D. 1822
415 controller knows that the consumer has not attained 13 years of age, the controller may not
426 process the consumer's data for any purpose without parental consent. If the controller
437 knows or willfully disregards that the consumer is at least 13 years of age but has not
448 attained 16 years of age, the controller may not process the consumer's data for targeted
459 advertising and must obtain the consumer's consent before processing the consumer's data
560 for sale.
7 The Act prohibits a controller from processing data in a manner that discriminates
8 against a person in violation of state or federal law. A controller is also prohibited from
9 retaliating against a consumer for exercising the consumer's rights under the Act, except
10 that a controller may offer different prices or selection of goods in connection with a
11 consumer's voluntary participation in a bona fide loyalty or discount program. A controller
12 must establish, implement and maintain reasonable data security practices. Beginning July
13 1, 2026, if a controller engages in a data processing activity that presents a heightened risk
14 of harm to a consumer, including processing any data for targeted advertising, sale or
15 profiling or any processing of sensitive data, the controller must conduct and document a
16 data protection assessment to identify and weigh the benefits and potential risks of the
17 processing activity. The controller may be required to disclose the data protection
18 assessment to the Attorney General, who must keep it confidential, when the assessment is
19 relevant to an investigation conducted by the Attorney General.
20 The provisions of the Act do not apply to specifically enumerated persons, including
21 the State, political subdivisions of the State and federally recognized Indian tribes in the
22 State; financial institutions or their affiliates subject to the federal Gramm-Leach-Bliley
23 Act; state-licensed and authorized insurers; covered entities and business associates subject
24 to the federal Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act of 1996; motor vehicle
25 dealer franchisees; nonprofits that do not receive any revenue from the sale of personal data
26 or that detect and prevent fraudulent insurance acts; and persons that both processed the
27 personal data of fewer than 25,000 consumers in the preceding calendar year and derived
28 no more than 25% of gross revenue from the sale of personal data. The Act also does not
29 apply to persons that controlled or processed the personal data for purposes other than
30 completing payment transactions of fewer than 100,000 consumers in the preceding
31 calendar year, except that, beginning January 1, 2028, this exception applies only to persons
32 that controlled or processed the personal data for purposes other than completing payment
33 transactions of fewer than 50,000 consumers in the preceding calendar year.
34 In addition, the provisions of the Act do not apply to specifically enumerated types of
35 data, including: nonpublic personal information regulated under the federal Gramm-Leach-
36 Bliley Act; health care information protected under the Maine Revised Statutes, Title 22,
37 section 1711-C; protected health information under the federal Health Insurance Portability
38 and Accountability Act of 1996; personal data regulated by the Family Educational Rights
39 and Privacy Act of 1974; data processed and maintained by the controller regarding an
40 applicant for employment or employee to the extent the data is collected and used within
41 the context of that role; and data necessary for the controller to administer benefits. The
42 Maine Consumer Data Privacy Act also does not prohibit controllers from engaging in
43 specifically enumerated activities, including complying with state or federal law;
44 complying with investigations or subpoenas from governmental authorities including the
45 Federal Government and the government of a state or a federally recognized Indian tribe
46 in the State; cooperating with federal, state or tribal law enforcement agencies; providing
Page 21 - 132LR0014(03)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 1220, L.D. 1822
417 a product or service specifically requested by the consumer; protecting life and physical
428 safety of consumers and preventing or responding to security incidents; and conducting
439 internal product research, effectuating a product recall or performing other internal
540 operations aligned with the expectations of a consumer.
5 Violations of the Act may be enforced exclusively by the Attorney General under the
6 Maine Unfair Trade Practices Act. The Attorney General is required to provide a potential
7 defendant with at least 30 days' notice prior to initiating an enforcement action, during
8 which time the potential defendant may cure any violation alleged in the notice. Any civil
9 penalties, attorney's fees or costs awarded to the State for a violation of the Act must be
10 deposited in the Maine Privacy Fund, which is established to provide funding for the
11 enforcement staff and activities of the Department of the Attorney General. The Act further
12 requires the Attorney General to submit a report by February 1, 2027 to the joint standing
13 committee of the Legislature having jurisdiction over judiciary matters regarding the
14 operation and implementation of the Act. The committee may report out legislation related
15 to the report to the 133rd Legislature in 2027.
16 The amendment also repeals the current law governing the privacy of broadband
17 Internet access service customer personal information because broadband Internet access
18 service providers are subject to the provisions of the Act.
